So we're waiting for those to come in. Adam, I'd love to hear, like, can you share a bit about your

00:04:34.959 --> 00:04:41.119
career path? And in particular, what advice you would give someone who's looking to transition

00:04:41.119 --> 00:04:47.839
from different kinds of fields or industries? Yeah, for sure. That's a very broad question.

00:04:48.559 --> 00:04:57.359
So let me think about where to start here. Sort of the themes that I've been thinking a lot about

00:04:57.359 --> 00:05:03.440
in terms of data science, and I call this out sort of in my bio, is that data science is really

00:05:04.079 --> 00:05:12.079
all about relationship building. So I was asked to give a guest lecture a couple years ago

00:05:12.079 --> 00:05:20.399
for students in an intro to data science course at UC San Diego. And so I felt a little bit,

00:05:20.399 --> 00:05:24.480
you know, kind of humbled by the invitation, and I thought, well, what would I say to

00:05:24.880 --> 00:05:29.600
the young kids coming into the field, right? Like, what are some of the things they might

00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:34.399
not learn about data science in their coursework, in the curriculum? And I thought, well,

00:05:35.440 --> 00:05:40.799
I really feel like the things that I had to learn on the job that were hardest to grasp were all

00:05:40.799 --> 00:05:46.399
about just what it means to have business relationships and sort of where data science

00:05:46.399 --> 00:05:52.480
actually fits in to the bigger picture. And I guess I like to start with sort of like this

00:05:52.480 --> 00:06:00.079
historical view of what data science is to help me think through this, too. So I think it was the

00:06:00.079 --> 00:06:07.519
Harvard Business Review in about 2012 was when they came out and said data science is the sexiest

00:06:07.519 --> 00:06:12.640
job of the 21st century. You probably all heard that said before, right? If you've worked in data

00:06:12.640 --> 00:06:18.160
science, you're kind of thinking, why would you ever say that? Because I think the reality was a

00:06:19.040 --> 00:06:25.519
little bit different. So I think when data science sort of rose up, I think the term was coined in

00:06:25.519 --> 00:06:32.559
like 2008 or something. And as it was on the rise, we really didn't have ML Ops. We really didn't

00:06:32.559 --> 00:06:37.200
have much in the way of DevOps. I think data engineering itself was just as new of a field.

00:06:37.920 --> 00:06:44.239
And companies really kind of jumped on the DS hype train really hard after that article was published.

00:06:44.320 --> 00:06:52.239
And organizations take a long time to mature analytically. And so I think some companies,

00:06:53.519 --> 00:06:59.200
I would say a lot of companies are there now, like our big tech companies. But a lot of companies

00:06:59.200 --> 00:07:06.320
are still going through this maturation. And especially in 2012, 2014, when I came on the scene,

00:07:06.320 --> 00:07:10.239
it was a time when companies were still figuring out that whole process.

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:14.239
But when this article was published, that kind of opened the floodgates

00:07:15.200 --> 00:07:21.279
for all these newly minted master's students like myself in stats to come into these companies,

00:07:21.279 --> 00:07:28.320
these newly forming departments, trying to make sense of what data they had available and kind

00:07:28.320 --> 00:07:34.640
of what to do with that. There were, I think, at the time when data science was sort of centralizing

00:07:35.600 --> 00:07:42.720
in a lot of these companies, you had a lot of embedded analysts that were doing what we would

00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:47.600
now call data science as part of their job. It just wasn't seen that way, or I guess it just

00:07:47.600 --> 00:07:54.079
wasn't called that with a label. And so as these specialized roles and departments were springing

00:07:54.079 --> 00:07:59.679
up, everybody was kind of trying to grapple with what data science meant. And I think that kind

00:07:59.679 --> 00:08:05.679
of like set the stage for a lot of interesting corporate dynamics where data science was trying

00:08:05.679 --> 00:08:10.320
to figure out what it was going to do in this business. And business people were trying to

00:08:10.320 --> 00:08:16.160
figure out who these new people were and what they were up to. And I think that led to a lot of

00:08:16.160 --> 00:08:22.720
sort of misunderstandings and a lot of confusion. And I think it has taken me a while to come to

00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:29.119
understand, come to terms with this idea of data science as being a tool for business. It's sort

00:08:29.119 --> 00:08:35.119
of one business function, and it's not just sort of like, it's not sort of every business is now

00:08:35.119 --> 00:08:41.039
going to be immediately data-driven, right? So, you know, I think about what advice would I give?

00:08:42.799 --> 00:08:47.359
Now I'll finally get your question. What advice would I give somebody? It's really about,

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:58.719
you know, understand what the business needs are. Don't build something before

00:09:00.719 --> 00:09:05.840
you're ready to understand where it's going to go and how it's going to get used. And I think that's

00:09:05.840 --> 00:09:12.159
sort of the crux of where I've made some of my mistakes. I remember after I left my first job,

00:09:12.159 --> 00:09:18.159
I was working for a vehicle manufacturer, and I was there for a couple years. I think we did some

00:09:18.159 --> 00:09:22.880
good work, but as I left the job, I was sort of reflecting on, you know, some of the things that

00:09:22.880 --> 00:09:26.719
didn't work out. I think I was surprised by a lot of the projects that failed, just how many there

00:09:26.719 --> 00:09:30.880
were, I guess, things where we tried to implement something and it just fell apart. And I actually

00:09:30.880 --> 00:09:38.000
took notes on some of this stuff because it was kind of amusing to me. It was a series of

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:43.359
model names that I had tried to build, and I had written notes like, this model worked, but the

00:09:43.359 --> 00:09:48.559
executives didn't understand it. Or I couldn't build the right business case around this, and

00:09:48.559 --> 00:09:56.159
the data was bad. Or the business stakeholder just stopped responding to my emails. Or the partner

00:09:56.159 --> 00:10:00.799
support fell through, and the project couldn't reach maturity. It was all just kind of notes like this,

00:10:00.799 --> 00:10:04.239
which was really interesting. And then as I went back and I looked at the things that did work,

00:10:04.239 --> 00:10:11.840
it was all about really simple answers to questions that my business partners were asking.

00:10:11.840 --> 00:10:17.840
So, you know, they needed to explore, for example, they needed to explore what are all the possible

00:10:17.840 --> 00:10:22.880
reasons we're seeing this one failure in this component of a truck. And they had all these

00:10:23.599 --> 00:10:27.679
hypotheses, and all they really needed to see at the end of the day was just a map of where

00:10:27.679 --> 00:10:31.039
the failures were happening and when they were happening. And that kind of sparked them to say,

00:10:31.039 --> 00:10:34.880
okay, now we know what the cause is. You know, it's probably temperature related. And they

00:10:34.880 --> 00:10:38.239
pursued that, and they found out that, yeah, in fact, it was temperature. And so it just saved

00:10:38.239 --> 00:10:43.599
them a bunch of time in that way. And it was just a simple, you know, map. And then, you know,

00:10:43.599 --> 00:10:48.400
it was just processes like that where you realize it's not always that you have to build a complicated

00:10:48.400 --> 00:10:56.000
model to answer a question. It's just figure out the right solution, even if it's not the,

00:10:56.400 --> 00:10:59.520
I guess, best solution, if that makes sense.

00:11:01.840 --> 00:11:07.679
Thank you. So that was a reflection on processes and data and things like that. So

00:11:07.679 --> 00:11:13.840
a question from Slido, forward thinking, how about AI? Do you find AI making its way

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:16.719
into you or your team's workflows? And how so?

00:11:18.159 --> 00:11:23.039
Yeah, this is a really interesting question that I was just talking with somebody about.

00:11:23.520 --> 00:11:31.440
Because this feels like a really huge paradigm shift. And the way I was thinking about this is

00:11:33.919 --> 00:11:40.880
my parents' generation sees people like me and younger, and there's this label they apply to us.

00:11:40.880 --> 00:11:46.320
It's the digital natives. I don't know if you've heard that, where you kind of grow up around

00:11:46.320 --> 00:11:51.840
technology, you grow up around computers, and you just have sort of a mental model of how those

00:11:51.840 --> 00:11:58.719
things work that is maybe different from somebody who started using them later in life. And so

00:11:58.719 --> 00:12:04.640
that's kind of like how my parents see this great divide between older and younger generations.

00:12:05.599 --> 00:12:11.919
And I always thought, is there going to be a similar kind of paradigm shift or seismic change

00:12:11.919 --> 00:12:18.400
in the way we think about things between me and my kids' generation? And I think maybe this new

00:12:19.359 --> 00:12:25.760
wave of generative AI is probably it in some ways, because it's really a different paradigm, a

00:12:25.760 --> 00:12:30.880
different way of thinking about technology and the access to information we have around us.

00:12:33.359 --> 00:12:40.159
And I begin to wonder whether that's going to be this sort of like permanent change in the way

00:12:40.159 --> 00:12:45.760
that we think about how we relate to the world, which I don't want to get too philosophical about

00:12:46.559 --> 00:12:51.039
or make too big a statement, but it does feel this way a little bit, because before you have,

00:12:51.039 --> 00:12:57.280
you know, as you're thinking about how do we introduce technology into our processes,

00:12:58.159 --> 00:13:04.719
you know, I would say 20 years ago it was, you know, evaluate what can be automated,

00:13:05.679 --> 00:13:12.479
sort of take all of the old functions you used to do, build this fixed core of sort of like

00:13:12.479 --> 00:13:19.200
technology and automation, and then sort of restructure your workflows around that fixed core.

00:13:20.479 --> 00:13:28.719
I think with technologies like gen AI, it's not like you have a deterministic fixed set of

00:13:28.719 --> 00:13:34.479
processes that take place at the core of your business or your work, and you structure everything

00:13:34.479 --> 00:13:38.880
around that. It's almost like, it's more like a relationship in a way. I guess going back to that

00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:46.239
theme of relationships, it feels like AI itself is going to, you know, like the way we'll use

00:13:46.239 --> 00:13:51.119
gen AI is going to be more like an assistant or, you know, an extra person you're working with,

00:13:51.119 --> 00:13:55.840
someone you have to kind of figure out how do you delegate tasks, how do you interact with the

00:13:55.840 --> 00:14:03.440
outputs and interpret those and polish those up for what you need, because it's not really as

00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:10.320
deterministic a system as you would have seen before. And so it's, yeah, it's

00:14:10.320 --> 00:14:15.679
going to be an interesting couple of years as we kind of figure out

00:14:15.679 --> 00:14:22.000
what to do with this thing, but I can say that, you know, my company is looking at, you know,

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:25.119
how you integrate this into your workflows. I know a lot of companies are thinking about

00:14:25.119 --> 00:14:27.280
what do you do with this, how do you make it,

00:14:27.359 --> 00:14:33.840
how do you build it in a way that is going to augment people's capacity, and how do you validate

00:14:33.840 --> 00:14:39.599
that it's giving you the right kinds of outputs, because there's lots of concerns around fairness

00:14:40.239 --> 00:14:46.239
and bias, and you think about how everyone has called things like XGBoost models black boxes.

00:14:46.239 --> 00:14:50.159
Well, I think gen AI is like the ultimate black box, right? So I think you're also going to see

00:14:50.159 --> 00:14:55.280
a lot of scrutiny around, you know, how these, you know, how do you, you know, how do you

00:14:55.679 --> 00:14:59.520
understand, you know, how these, how can you interpret what these things are doing, and how do

00:14:59.520 --> 00:15:05.840
you ensure that they're providing accurate, and fair, and safe outputs.

00:15:08.400 --> 00:15:11.119
Yeah, absolutely. That's definitely been my experience with

00:15:11.119 --> 00:15:13.760
chat GPT, just like how do I make you useful?

00:15:14.960 --> 00:15:17.440
I know, yeah, I think that's really interesting. I think, like,

00:15:18.880 --> 00:15:22.799
it's so early days, and if you've just kind of messed around with chat GPT a little bit,

00:15:23.760 --> 00:15:31.039
it's both going to, I guess, like, awe you and concern you, I think, you know, because you'll

00:15:31.039 --> 00:15:35.840
spend a lot of time, you know, you can do things like, hey, I think the first thing I tried with

00:15:35.840 --> 00:15:45.919
it was write me a Hallmark movie script about, you know, somebody who reconnects with a high

00:15:45.919 --> 00:15:52.080
school sweetheart in winter or something, and so it generated the script, and then I said,

00:15:52.080 --> 00:15:56.799
okay, turn this into a country song, and it did that, and it rhymed and everything,

00:15:56.799 --> 00:15:59.919
it was so cool, and then I said, okay, make it like a zombie movie, and then,

00:16:00.960 --> 00:16:05.760
so it kept the country song structure, and gave me zombies in there, and it was a lot of fun,

00:16:05.760 --> 00:16:10.400
and that's, like, wow, this is, like, this is game changing, and then you go, and you say,

00:16:11.919 --> 00:16:17.760
write some code to, you know, complete this task, and it'll totally make up a package,

00:16:17.760 --> 00:16:23.119
or totally invent functions, right, so it's a real mixed bag.

00:16:24.479 --> 00:16:31.039
Definitely. So going back to something that you mentioned earlier, Abigail has a question.

