commuters? I think they had, had a data set on, or a column about, are you a subscriber,

00:20:13.520 --> 00:20:17.599
or just, like, a one-time user? So you can kind of begin to explore and say, you know, what,

00:20:17.760 --> 00:20:23.199
what are the attributes that, that, that determine when bikes will be used the most, and

00:20:24.160 --> 00:20:28.160
where are they going, and how can you think about turning that into, like, a business

00:20:28.160 --> 00:20:32.160
problem where it's, you know, optimizing the location of bikes and things like that.

00:20:33.520 --> 00:20:37.920
But yeah, just find, find a topic that, that, like, you really enjoy and are interested in,

00:20:37.920 --> 00:20:41.199
and that will kind of lead you to the right kinds of questions and analyses.

00:20:41.520 --> 00:20:42.020
Thank you.

00:20:43.760 --> 00:20:47.680
Lydia, I saw you had a question. Would you mind jumping in? And I saw there was quite a bit of

00:20:47.680 --> 00:20:53.920
discussion, so if anybody has other thoughts. Sure. I think this is a situation that a lot of

00:20:53.920 --> 00:21:00.959
people have found themselves in. My question was, what would you, what advice would you give a

00:21:01.520 --> 00:21:08.319
younger or newer data team on how to either avoid or stop being just a ticket-taking center,

00:21:08.319 --> 00:21:15.599
ticket-taking center, and become a value creation center that is doing projects that are meaningful

00:21:15.599 --> 00:21:21.119
and that have meaningful KPIs and have backers and stuff like that? That's a transition that I,

00:21:21.119 --> 00:21:27.760
I find a lot of teams have a hard time making. And as I interview with, with places, potential

00:21:27.760 --> 00:21:31.599
places, that's something I ask about interviews. Like, how do you intake stuff? Do you have an

00:21:31.599 --> 00:21:35.359
intake process? If you don't, I worry that you're, you're not protecting people's time,

00:21:35.359 --> 00:21:41.520
stuff like that. So, I'm wondering your thoughts. Oh man, such an important question.

00:21:45.199 --> 00:21:51.839
Yeah, I saw this interesting LinkedIn post the other day where somebody, I think he worked at

00:21:51.839 --> 00:22:00.880
a big tech company, and he was saying, he's like, data scientists, stop being, or stop taking

00:22:00.880 --> 00:22:07.439
requirements. And, and it was all about sort of get yourself a seat at the table, make sure that

00:22:07.439 --> 00:22:16.719
you are defining strategic direction and, and pushing that forward. And I, I had like a mixed

00:22:16.719 --> 00:22:21.119
reaction to that because I think on the one hand, yeah, that's right. Like, I think, I think a data

00:22:21.119 --> 00:22:26.560
driven organization needs to be thinking about how to advance their data capabilities. And that's

00:22:26.719 --> 00:22:32.160
the only way that you reach this, like, analytics maturity. And when I say, I keep saying analytics

00:22:32.160 --> 00:22:36.560
maturity, what I mean is sort of like, a lot of organizations go through this process of

00:22:38.560 --> 00:22:44.000
starting out where they're sort of using descriptive analytics, where it's a lot of

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:47.599
sort of reporting and understanding what happened in the past and that sort of thing. And then they

00:22:47.599 --> 00:22:54.719
move into more predictive analytics, where it's sort of like model building, you know, maybe using

00:22:54.719 --> 00:23:00.959
their predictions before business processes somewhere. And then they move into the space of

00:23:00.959 --> 00:23:05.439
sort of like prescriptive analytics, where it's like, okay, here's, here's, you know, the, the

00:23:05.439 --> 00:23:12.239
actions we should be taking as a result of these, of these more complex analytics initiatives. So,

00:23:14.719 --> 00:23:18.880
so, so I think it partly depends on kind of like where you are in that, in that analytics

00:23:18.959 --> 00:23:25.680
maturity curve. But I do think it's, it's okay in some respects to,

00:23:27.680 --> 00:23:30.800
to, I don't want to say take tickets, but I want to say,

00:23:32.800 --> 00:23:40.959
sort of build within the requirements of a business partner's set, broader set of goals.

00:23:41.520 --> 00:23:47.199
And so I'll explain kind of what I mean by that. A business is going to have this sort of like

00:23:47.199 --> 00:23:53.199
overarching goal, and that's usually like selling stuff, right? And then that, and then to achieve

00:23:53.199 --> 00:23:59.439
that goal, you, you kind of break that down into these core sets of business strategies.

00:24:00.479 --> 00:24:04.239
And then within each strategy, which might be owned by different kinds of like business divisions,

00:24:05.280 --> 00:24:11.599
you have a number of decisions in order to, to execute on initiatives that support the strategy.

00:24:12.400 --> 00:24:17.040
And then, and then to make those decisions, you have to have evidence that you're going to do the

00:24:17.040 --> 00:24:24.000
right thing. And that evidence, you know, I think among the evidence you have, one piece of that is

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:32.640
your, is your data. And among all of your, your data evidence, one piece of that is things that,

00:24:32.640 --> 00:24:38.800
that your data science team can do, can show, can prove. And so I think,

00:24:42.400 --> 00:24:46.800
that also kind of depends on sort of how your data science organization is, is built within

00:24:46.800 --> 00:24:51.680
the business. So I want to add some caveats there, but generally, you know, you'll have like different

00:24:51.680 --> 00:24:56.800
data science functions, whether they're so like centralized, but broken into like different

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:02.719
groups based on sort of who they're supporting in the business, or they're maybe more like embedded

00:25:03.599 --> 00:25:07.920
within a team, but you kind of have a function that you're supporting. And so I think it's

00:25:07.920 --> 00:25:15.599
important to, this is where it's, it's not quite requirement taking, but it's working with your

00:25:15.599 --> 00:25:19.920
business partners to understand what their strategies are that, that ultimately roll up

00:25:19.920 --> 00:25:25.760
to that overarching goal for that division, right? Because they need to achieve some kind of,

00:25:26.959 --> 00:25:34.959
like you said, the KPIs and the metrics, right? And so if, if they're the ones who are generally

00:25:34.959 --> 00:25:41.119
going to set the strategy, and then what you need to do is, in those cases, work with them and say,

00:25:41.119 --> 00:25:50.000
like, what are those decisions that you're making? What are the sort of metrics or, or quantities

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:56.000
that, that will tell you how to make those decisions? And then where do I plug in from there?

00:25:56.000 --> 00:26:02.479
So it is a little bit about understanding the requirements of the business from that standpoint.

00:26:02.479 --> 00:26:06.319
However, you can also push back, and this stuff, I think, is where data scientists can have a lot

00:26:06.319 --> 00:26:11.119
of value, but also get themselves in a lot of trouble. You can push back on those metrics or

00:26:11.119 --> 00:26:15.520
on those ideas and say, well, what if we measured this thing over here instead? You know, would that

00:26:15.520 --> 00:26:22.400
be valuable? And I think, like, the value add there is, is now you can strategically shift the way

00:26:22.400 --> 00:26:28.160
they're thinking about how to measure things, and the, you know, kinds of, kinds of data that they

00:26:28.160 --> 00:26:31.839
collect, and what they can do with that information. You also want to be careful, because

00:26:34.239 --> 00:26:41.599
in, in, in my experience, it's, it's, it's easy to sort of get a little too critical

00:26:41.599 --> 00:26:45.920
of the way that business is done, because I do think data scientists, I think our, you know, one

00:26:45.920 --> 00:26:53.599
of our strengths is to sort of see, you know, it's like, like, we see the numbers, we see the patterns,

00:26:53.599 --> 00:26:59.520
we are pretty good at sort of going from those numbers to, like, outcomes, and so it's, it's easy

00:26:59.520 --> 00:27:05.199
to sort of push too early to change the way the business is thinking about a metric. Sometimes we

00:27:05.199 --> 00:27:10.560
have to sort of, like, live into the way things are done, and then introduce alternative ways of

00:27:10.560 --> 00:27:16.160
looking at it at the same time. Thank you. And Matthew, I see that you have a hand raised.

00:27:17.920 --> 00:27:21.760
Thanks. I wanted to add a comment, because this has been a huge part of my

00:27:22.239 --> 00:27:27.119
journey. I've been a data scientist, and also data analyst for the past 10 years. I'm

00:27:27.119 --> 00:27:32.479
now a data analyst at GitHub for the past two years, focusing on sales, and that's been,

00:27:33.280 --> 00:27:39.439
when we talked about, let's say, not being a ticket, not just being a ticket receiving center,

00:27:40.239 --> 00:27:43.680
the model that I try to think of, especially when I'm working with salespeople,

00:27:44.640 --> 00:27:49.439
it's in, it's a collaboration, but they're the lead, and that's sometimes the hard thing,

00:27:50.239 --> 00:27:55.280
when we think about the project that we're working on, that if it's something we're

00:27:55.280 --> 00:27:58.880
interested in, but it doesn't solve a business question for a stakeholder, the project doesn't

00:27:58.880 --> 00:28:03.439
matter. In the end, the project always has to be tailored to that business question from the

00:28:03.439 --> 00:28:08.160
stakeholder. It's something that's really helped me, just asking the basic questions of, what are

00:28:08.160 --> 00:28:12.319
they trying to do? The different roles have different responsibilities, and a lot of times,

00:28:12.319 --> 00:28:16.160
people assume that I know their basic responsibilities, but for the most part,

00:28:16.160 --> 00:28:23.839
I normally don't, so I guess I wanted to put that comment out there to see if anyone else

00:28:23.839 --> 00:28:30.319
has thought about it in that way, that it's a collaboration, but they're the lead,

00:28:30.319 --> 00:28:34.239
and asking the basic questions about, what are they trying to do? What are they trying to get

00:28:34.239 --> 00:28:38.160
out of the project? Because then it becomes much easier to push back on certain things,

00:28:38.160 --> 00:28:45.599
if I know what their vision is and what they want. Yeah, really important point, and I think that's

00:28:45.599 --> 00:28:52.959
where a lot of early data science groups struggled, I know I did, is to let the other

00:28:52.959 --> 00:29:00.959
people lead, in a lot of ways, because we're really good at doing analysis, so we can tell

00:29:00.959 --> 00:29:07.119
when something is going wrong, and so it's hard to let people lead when you think there's a better

00:29:07.119 --> 00:29:14.800
way, but this reminds me of a really nice blog post that Ted Lederis wrote just a couple days

00:29:14.800 --> 00:29:22.160
ago, he calls it, yes, and is the foundation of collaboration, if somebody happens to have that

00:29:22.160 --> 00:29:29.439
link, maybe throw it in the chat, but he takes this idea from improv comedy, it's this idea

00:29:29.439 --> 00:29:32.959
called, yes, and, and if you haven't heard of this, it's basically, you know, when you're doing

00:29:32.959 --> 00:29:37.839
improv comedy, you might have sort of a scenario, but you don't really have an idea of what's going

00:29:37.839 --> 00:29:42.000
to happen, right, you don't know the direction this thing's going to take, there's no script,

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:47.760
obviously, and so there's this idea in improv called, yes, and, in which sort of, you know,

00:29:47.760 --> 00:29:52.640
somebody will say something, or introduce a new idea to this scenario, and then it's your

00:29:52.640 --> 00:29:58.239
partner's job to sort of take that idea and carry it forward, push the idea forward, keep running

00:29:58.239 --> 00:30:04.319
with it, and not to say no, because that kind of interrupts the flow of, of a comedy sketch, and if

00:30:04.319 --> 00:30:09.680
you've, if you watched, if you watch The Office, you've probably seen Michael Scott do the exact

00:30:09.680 --> 00:30:14.000
wrong thing in his improv comedy classes, where he'll just like come in and completely upend

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:22.000
whatever is happening, and it's hilarious, but anyway, so, so in this blog post, Ted says that

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:28.640
in collaboration, you build on what your partner is doing, and that's like this, I think that one

00:30:28.640 --> 00:30:33.040
sentence really stuck out to me, like, yeah, I think that's kind of where I see data science

00:30:33.760 --> 00:30:40.719
and relationships really kind of like taking off, it's sort of, yeah, like you said, letting them lead,

00:30:40.719 --> 00:30:46.319
building on what they're doing by, by enhancing it, by adding new ways of measurement, maybe being

00:30:46.319 --> 00:30:52.400
more precise, and maybe finding new ways to, to identify, you know, sort of the, the things that

00:30:52.400 --> 00:30:57.760
lead to the ultimate business success, and the other piece of that is like data science,

00:30:58.959 --> 00:31:03.280
I think at the end of that, that movie, so, so, Soylent Green, where the guy is being carried

00:31:03.280 --> 00:31:07.199
away, and he's like, Soylent Green is people, I always think about that, because I'm like, data science is

00:31:07.199 --> 00:31:13.040
people, and, and I think like data science, you know, it's, it's all about the people, I think people are

00:31:13.040 --> 00:31:20.160
political, I think of politics as sort of like this combination of power and motivations,

00:31:21.760 --> 00:31:27.680
I don't think that data science influences power directly necessarily, but it can certainly engage

00:31:27.680 --> 00:31:35.839
with people's motivations, and so once you identify what their motivations are, and, you know, then you

00:31:35.839 --> 00:31:42.959
can work within the context of those motivations to be more successful. Thank you, and Rick, I see

00:31:42.959 --> 00:31:49.920
that you've had your hand up as well. Oh, thank you, Isabella, and Adam, really appreciate your

00:31:49.920 --> 00:31:57.040
remarks. Quick question, by way of background, I am, I spent four decades in the industry as a

00:31:57.040 --> 00:32:02.560
practitioner, and one decade as a university professor, and now I'm kind of retired from both,

00:32:02.560 --> 00:32:08.079
but I still, you know, am involved, we'll just say that I take on projects from time to time.

00:32:10.479 --> 00:32:17.680
Two questions for you, Adam, if you'd be so kind. The first is, I really appreciate your remarks

00:32:17.680 --> 00:32:24.239
about, for example, looking at GitHub profiles as you're evaluating, especially early career

00:32:24.959 --> 00:32:30.079
candidates, and people that might be just starting off in the field. I thought your

00:32:30.079 --> 00:32:36.079
approach is very purposeful and insightful, and I hope that everyone adopts something similar,

00:32:37.199 --> 00:32:43.199
but would you comment on your perspectives, particularly in a regulated industry like

00:32:43.199 --> 00:32:50.959
insurance, how long do you feel it takes somebody with good data science skills, let's say that's

00:32:50.959 --> 00:32:57.599
the x dimension, to also acquire good domain skills and deep enough understanding in the

00:32:57.599 --> 00:33:03.839
domain, which I'll call the vertical axis, to the point where they can be a trusted advisor

00:33:03.839 --> 00:33:08.719
to our business partners? That's the first question. The second one is,

00:33:11.119 --> 00:33:18.239
it's not actually a question, it's a philosophy. My philosophy in projects has been, and I've

00:33:18.239 --> 00:33:22.959
worked on tiny, tiny, tiny projects, and hundred million dollar efforts, and everything in between,

00:33:23.920 --> 00:33:29.920
is if I knew enough about running the business to tell the people running the business

00:33:29.920 --> 00:33:36.640
how to run the business, I would be running the business. I feel I'm there as an advisor,

00:33:36.640 --> 00:33:44.640
as a resource, my job is to understand the strategic and tactical needs of the business,

00:33:44.640 --> 00:33:52.239
my customer, if you will, and translate that into technology in some form, data science,

00:33:52.239 --> 00:33:58.319
maybe it's just data visualization, or something like that, that helps them achieve their goals.

00:33:58.959 --> 00:34:03.599
I would welcome your perspectives on both of those remarks, Adam. Thank you.

00:34:04.959 --> 00:34:14.560
Yeah, thanks, Rick. The timing question is tricky, it's another one of those things where

00:34:15.120 --> 00:34:21.760
I'm always going to say it depends, and it's not just because I'm trying to cover my butt,

00:34:22.479 --> 00:34:31.040
but I think your first question is, how long does it take to sort of get up to speed

00:34:31.040 --> 00:34:38.399
within your business, especially if you're coming in sort of early career, in order to

00:34:38.399 --> 00:34:44.959
be that trusted advisor, to be able to work with people. Yeah, it's going to depend a lot on

00:34:45.679 --> 00:34:51.120
the way that the business is going to onboard people, so I've seen,

00:34:51.840 --> 00:34:57.760
I've worked in big companies and small, and a small company, and I think the difference is,

00:34:58.959 --> 00:35:05.840
you know, in the small companies, the onboarding is a little bit less structured, and you're kind

00:35:05.840 --> 00:35:11.679
of left to your own devices to kind of get set up, and in a lot of cases, you're very charitable,

00:35:11.760 --> 00:35:16.159
Adam. Yeah, yeah, I'm trying to become, like I said, data science is all about people,

00:35:16.159 --> 00:35:18.639
and people are all about politics, so that's what I'm trying to play into here,

00:35:20.800 --> 00:35:25.679
but in big companies, oftentimes, and not always, you're going to have an onboarding program,

00:35:25.679 --> 00:35:31.199
or maybe even a training program that will kind of introduce you, at least high level,

00:35:31.199 --> 00:35:35.840
to the concepts you're going to need. So my first insurance job, there was a lot of new

00:35:36.080 --> 00:35:41.040
training, which was a really cool program, where we learned a lot about, you know, how we do

00:35:41.040 --> 00:35:44.479
programming here, how you might do version control, all the technical stuff, but then also,

00:35:44.479 --> 00:35:47.919
so like, what is insurance, you know, and like, how does, you know, how does it work,

00:35:47.919 --> 00:35:52.560
how does it break down? The other thing you're going to have to do, I think, when your early

00:35:52.560 --> 00:36:03.120
career is, and I don't say this lightly, because I know it's not the most fun thing, but it's

00:36:03.120 --> 00:36:08.399
probably just attend a lot of meetings, and pay close attention to kind of what's happening,

00:36:08.399 --> 00:36:14.560
and understand sort of who the people are in those meetings, what they care about,

00:36:15.199 --> 00:36:20.159
how they're relating to one another, and then identifying, you know, when you're in these

00:36:20.159 --> 00:36:25.199
meetings, what numbers are they sort of monitoring, or checking, why are they checking those things,

00:36:26.159 --> 00:36:29.600
you know, and then as you talk to your mentors, or your peers, you can say,

00:36:29.600 --> 00:36:34.879
what are the kinds of data do we have that kind of relates to this, and that gives you kind of a

00:36:34.879 --> 00:36:38.879
good starting point for thinking about, okay, are we measuring this the right way, and then what

00:36:38.879 --> 00:36:42.879
other ways do we think about this, and then you go to these meetings, and you can understand sort of

00:36:42.879 --> 00:36:48.159
what people are after, right, like, it's like, it goes back to that question of like, I mean,

00:36:48.159 --> 00:36:54.560
you have a goal, to reach your goal, you're building strategies, and you're making decisions

00:36:54.560 --> 00:36:58.959
to support those strategies, so what decisions are they making, and then you just ask a lot

00:36:58.959 --> 00:37:04.159
of questions about sort of how those decisions are being made, why they're being made, and then,

00:37:04.159 --> 00:37:10.239
you know, what other evidence they might need to make better decisions. I think maybe that's

00:37:10.239 --> 00:37:15.679
the key to sort of get into a place where they start trusting you, is you're saying, I can,

00:37:15.679 --> 00:37:19.199
you know, I can bring some value, but I want you to kind of tell me what it is you need,

00:37:20.639 --> 00:37:25.439
instead of just building something and saying, here it is, or would it be helpful if you knew x,

00:37:25.439 --> 00:37:30.239
y, and z, because someone's always going to say, yes, I want you to, you know, yes, I want that

00:37:30.239 --> 00:37:33.760
knowledge. People always want more knowledge, even if they have no idea what they're going to do with

00:37:33.760 --> 00:37:40.479
it, so if you can, if you can work to frame something in terms of, let's find the actionable

00:37:40.479 --> 00:37:46.080
pieces of information, you know, by asking them what they need to make better decisions, I think that

00:37:46.080 --> 00:37:52.879
that gives you good footing to start with, and yeah, hope that answers your question.

